# Accessibility Guidelines

## POUR Principles
- Perceivable: Information must be presentable in ways all users can perceive
  - Provide text alternatives for non-text content
  - Provide captions and alternatives for multimedia
  - Create content that can be presented in different ways
  - Make it easier for users to see and hear content
  
- Operable: Interface components must be operable by all users
  - Make all functionality available from a keyboard
  - Give users enough time to read and use content
  - Avoid content that could cause seizures or physical reactions
  - Help users navigate and find content
  - Make it easier to use inputs other than keyboard
  
- Understandable: Information and operation must be understandable
  - Make text readable and understandable
  - Make content appear and operate in predictable ways
  - Help users avoid and correct mistakes
  
- Robust: Content must be robust enough to work with current and future technologies
  - Maximize compatibility with current and future user tools

## WCAG 2.1 Compliance
- Aim for at least AA compliance level
- Use semantic HTML elements
- Implement proper heading structure (h1-h6)
- Include proper alt text for images
- Ensure keyboard navigability
- Maintain focus visibility
- Provide sufficient color contrast
- Support screen readers with ARIA when necessary
- Test with actual assistive technologies

## Common Accessibility Patterns
- Skip navigation links
- Proper form labels and error handling
- Consistent navigation
- Descriptive link text (avoid "click here")
- Responsive design that works at 200% zoom
- Support for reduced motion preferences
